'''George Hartshorn Hodges''' ([[February 6]], [[1866]] <U+2013> [[October 7]], [[1947]]) was an [[United States|American]] [[politician]] and the nineteenth [[Governor of Kansas]] (1913 <U+2013> 1915). Before elected governor, he served in the [[Kansas Legislature|state legislature]] as a [[Kansas Senate|senator]] from 1905 to 1913, where he was particularly active on the railroad committee in the senate and known for leading the charge for [[Progressivism|progressive]] laws for the state of Kansas.<ref>http://skyways.lib.ks.us/genweb/archives/1918ks/bioh/hodgesgh.html</ref>

The administration of Governor Hodges brought the following changes:
*a corporation tax was sanctioned
*a women's [[suffrage]] amendment to the state constitution was authorized
*the board of administration was granted power to control all state agencies
*women's roles were advanced in state government.<ref>http://www.nga.org/portal/site/nga/menuitem.29fab9fb4add37305ddcbeeb501010a0/?vgnextoid=005d224971c81010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD&vgnextchannel=e449a0ca9e3f1010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD</ref>

After losing his reelection bid, Hodges returned to his various business interests as he had established a successful career as a businessman.  His business holdings included the lumber, hardware, and loan industries.  He also owned a newspaper, the ''Johnson County Democrat''.<ref>http://www.nga.org/portal/site/nga/menuitem.29fab9fb4add37305ddcbeeb501010a0/?vgnextoid=005d224971c81010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD&vgnextchannel=e449a0ca9e3f1010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD</ref>

